I haven&#39;t run into this problem before. I suppose you&#39;re decreasing the 
enthalpy by calling &#39;setState_HP&#39; first with the desired enthalpy and 
pressure and initial composition.  I bet the problem is that the 
resulting initial temperature is so low that it is either out of range 
for the thermo data, or causes numerical problems for other reasons.

Can you run the problem fixing (T,P) rather than (H,P)?

You might also try the new equilibrium solver, which doesn&#39;t use 
ChemEquil.  In Python, you can access it by creating a &#39;Mixture&#39; 
containing the gas phase:

gas = GRI30()
mix = Mixture([(gas, 1.0)])
mix.equilibrate(&#39;HP&#39;)
print mix

And if you want to include a condensed phase, you can do it like this:
gas = GRI30()
carbon = importPhase(&#39;graphite.cti&#39;)
mix = Mixture([(gas, 1.0), (carbon, 0.0)])
mix.equilibrate(&#39;HP&#39;)
print mix

Depending on the version of Cantera you have this may or may not work.  
It definitely works with the prerelease of version 1.6, available by 
CVS.

Dave


